00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:35.720
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:44.480
Can't wait to see you there. I am super excited to introduce our guest today. Our guest is

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:52.580
Toby Hall, EVP and CIO at Delta Dental of Michigan. Toby, that is a mouthful. I would

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:56.480
love it if you could introduce yourself, tell us a little bit about what you do and what

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:57.919
you like to do for fun.

00:00:57.919 --> 00:01:04.919
Sure. I'm excited to be here. My name is Toby Hall. As Libby said, I'm the Executive Vice

00:01:04.919 --> 00:01:11.360
President and CIO for Delta Dental of Michigan. We are actually the headquarters here for

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:16.120
three different Deltas, Delta Dental of Michigan, Ohio, and Indiana. We're a little bit like

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:20.959
the Blue Cross system where notionally there's a Delta Dental in every state. And we forever

00:01:20.959 --> 00:01:27.440
have run our entire business on a homegrown IT system. And I lead the team that owns and

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:33.040
maintains that. I've got about 500 or so, 510. We kind of swell in the summer with interns.

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:38.279
So the report I got last week, I think we have a team of about 510 total. By training,

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:43.959
I'm an actuary. That's where I first was exposed to R, spent the first 20 some years of my

00:01:43.959 --> 00:01:49.000
career doing actuarial work, many of those as chief actuary for Delta. So excited to

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:50.400
be here.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:53.760
And what is something that you like to do for fun? Everybody always forgets that part.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:58.879
Oh, yeah. Oh, good call. So for fun, I have two kiddos. So a lot of time is spent chasing

00:01:58.879 --> 00:02:04.440
them, going to their different sporting events and school events, reading, and ironically

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:08.759
staying up on R, still do a lot of R coding, just hobbyist on the side.

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:14.679
Oh, as do we all. Well, it's wonderful to have you. I will remind everybody really quickly

00:02:14.679 --> 00:02:18.399
for anybody who just popped in because the waiting room is still going. Hey, waiting

00:02:18.399 --> 00:02:24.800
room people who just came in, welcome. You can ask questions in Slido for Toby today.

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:30.399
So my first question is usually always a context building question that'll help us ask questions.

00:02:30.399 --> 00:02:38.839
So Toby, tell me a little bit about your day to day, but also the data teams at Delta Dental

00:02:38.839 --> 00:02:44.000
of Michigan. What is the type of data that they work with and what is it that they solve

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.679
with it or what decisions are made based on it?

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.880
Yeah, that's a great question. So my day to day, I would say there really isn't a day

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:56.160
to day. It's always different. With that breadth of the application that we support and the

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:59.880
number of team members, there's always something going on, something different. It's a lot

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:04.679
of project management type tasks though. Staying on top of large initiatives, marching towards

00:03:04.679 --> 00:03:11.800
go live. With insurance, we're very heavily regulated. So there's a lot of data security,

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:16.320
things that take up a lot of my time. And then just in the last 18 months, it's obviously

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:21.880
been AI is the big kind of buzzword right now. Try and understand how we're using it.

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:26.960
Should we be using it? What's an appropriate use of AI? A lot of work there. One of the

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:31.360
teams, and this gets into the second half of your question, one of the teams that reports

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:35.279
up to me is our data science team. And I saw earlier, Shikha Mohindra, our principal data

00:03:35.279 --> 00:03:40.080
scientist joined and she had IM'd me earlier that she was going to join. So at some point,

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:42.639
Shikha, I may have to ask you to come off mute. You may have to bail me out on some

00:03:42.639 --> 00:03:49.800
questions. But with that being said, we stood up a data science team a few years ago. It's

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:55.160
a team that economically, you have to be at a certain scale for it to make sense. Data

00:03:55.160 --> 00:04:00.919
scientists, to do it right, you need a balanced team, domain experts, some more, I would say

00:04:00.919 --> 00:04:06.360
like statistics, modeling experts, some technology experts. It's really hard to find that one

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:10.880
unicorn person or small team that can do it. So you really, to enter that and do it well,

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:14.320
you need a critical, massive team, four or five, six people. You can't do it with two.

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:19.760
It's probably not going to work. And then that being said, those resources are not the cheapest

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.440
resources. So you got to have a certain scale to your business for that to make economic sense.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:28.640
And we crossed over that bridge a few years ago and we got approval to build out a data science

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:35.040
team. Shikha was a core person. We sort of built that team around. The data they use is,

00:04:35.679 --> 00:04:39.760
it's insurance data. So it's pretty much what you would expect. It's data about our network

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:44.559
providers, dentist data, where they're practicing, how many patients they're seeing,

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:46.799
how long they've been in our network, that type of data.

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:54.480
Then claims data is a big one. Claims effectively, the way we ought to be looking at that in a

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:58.399
highly transactional world is claims are effectively a receipt for the care that got

00:04:58.399 --> 00:05:02.880
rendered. So there's a lot of richness to the data there and then eligibility data.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:08.480
So the provider data tells us who performed the service, the claim is what was done,

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:12.399
and then the eligibility tells us who got the service, who was in the chair getting the dental

00:05:12.399 --> 00:05:16.160
treatments. And there's a lot of different use cases for that. And we have to look at that data

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:19.920
differently. At times we're looking at it as cross-sectional data, sometimes it's more

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:26.559
longitudinal. We've had some great wins lately with quality of care type models and data work

00:05:26.559 --> 00:05:31.359
that we've built. We've built some great apps that our teams can use out in the field,

00:05:32.239 --> 00:05:36.959
powered in the background with a lot of heavy lifting and a lot of hard work, a lot of Python

00:05:36.959 --> 00:05:45.359
being done in the back on that. So that rounds out the data. I'm trying to think through what

00:05:45.359 --> 00:05:48.880
data we wish we had, because it's always great to think about the data you have, but the data

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:55.679
we wish we had. We've just recently started bringing in third-party data where we can buy

00:05:55.679 --> 00:06:00.559
or rent data from third parties. And we're still trying to get our arms around the best uses of

00:06:00.559 --> 00:06:03.760
that. We're probably not as mature as we need to be, but we're getting much better.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:08.640
Oh, that was going to be my next question was, what about third-party data? How does that work?

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:12.160
And so that's always something that's really interesting to me. And I know when we've talked

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:17.679
with other insurance folks in other areas, not health insurance or dental insurance,

00:06:17.679 --> 00:06:21.839
more property and casualty insurance, that third-party data is such a huge thing.

00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:26.799
But I don't know what that looks like when you're talking about health and when you're talking about

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:34.320
dentistry. Yeah. So third-party data in PNC is, you're right, it's super valuable. Data from the

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:39.440
US flood surveys, that type of thing. And that's obviously going to be a huge thing for PNC

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:47.440
actuaries. When we think third-party data in our world, it's honestly more around how can we get a

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:52.559
more full picture of provider behavior? And we're really looking for either end of the curve.

00:06:53.519 --> 00:06:57.279
We have an obligation, a moral obligation to be looking out for fraud, waste, and abuse.

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:02.079
So we're looking at that. And that is a tiny, tiny fraction of the dentistry going on out there.

00:07:02.079 --> 00:07:05.920
The other end of the curve though, what are those dentists that are providing just excellent care,

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:10.480
excellent patterns of behavior, conservative dentistry, they're keeping their patients

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:14.079
healthy for the long-term. Those are the dentists we want to look at. We want to reward those

00:07:14.079 --> 00:07:21.119
dentists. And sometimes we're looking at third-party data to do that. I'll zoom in on one

00:07:21.119 --> 00:07:28.559
side, on the fraud side. We did get data around financial behaviors. And no surprise, you find a

00:07:28.559 --> 00:07:33.679
dentist that's got tax liens and has filed for bankruptcy and maybe has borrowed money a bunch

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:37.600
in the last couple of months. And yeah, that's a dentist we want to take a look at. On the other

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:41.440
side, you've got dentists who have gotten awards clinical. Well, we want to know that too. Those

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:44.559
are dentists we want to look at on the other end of the bell curve. So we're looking at both ends.

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:49.519
Awesome. Well, I have some questions rolling in through Slido. So even though I have some

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:56.720
of my own, mine are going to wait just a second. So let's go over to a Slido question. Arsenis

00:07:56.720 --> 00:08:01.119
asked a question. Arsenis, I'm going to highlight your question in Slido so everybody can see it.

00:08:01.119 --> 00:08:08.640
And also, if you are able to unmute, you can ask yours. Awesome. Thanks, Libby. Hi. And thank you,

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:14.000
Toby, for joining us. My question is actually really simple, something that you just said.

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:21.119
So you mentioned that you were introduced to R in your kind of studying actuarial and all that.

00:08:21.839 --> 00:08:27.679
But your team also uses Python for certain things. So I was wondering if you could discuss maybe how

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:36.400
you all decide which language to use and for what applications, and maybe how you use them

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:41.520
kind of interact, like going from one to the other. Yeah, this is a great question. And this

00:08:41.599 --> 00:08:47.280
is one, even I asked the team the same question. So you're not wrong. I would say the four main

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:53.119
languages or tool sets that are used in that area, we do get a lot of data pulled and manipulated

00:08:53.119 --> 00:08:58.719
through SAS, which is SAS was here when I came here in 2003. I'm not sure if we were building

00:08:58.719 --> 00:09:03.840
it out today, we would be using SAS, frankly. But it serves a purpose. We're highly transactional

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:08.559
in data. SAS, the way it operates is very much process one row at a time. That's the way our

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:17.359
data is structured. The paradigm works fine. Then R, Python, and then just like core grassroots SQL

00:09:17.359 --> 00:09:22.719
kind of work. Those would be the four biggies. And I would argue we are at that point now where

00:09:22.719 --> 00:09:28.640
it's sort of modeler's choice, whatever you're most comfortable with. Sometimes we have a few

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:33.200
hurdles with our IT security team getting things downloaded onto laptops and things. We've got

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:38.000
things tightened, buttoned down pretty tight as we should. But in general, it's modeler's choice

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.400
and whatever they're most comfortable with. I am seeing a huge shift though in the last five years.

00:09:43.679 --> 00:09:49.679
Youngsters getting out of college very much on the Python wagon. R is a little bit less common

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:53.359
now that I'm out of the Actuarial area. If I put my toe back in the Actuarial area, I think I'd see

00:09:53.359 --> 00:10:02.320
a lot more R than I do today. Great question, Arsenis. Thank you so much. All right. I saw a

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:06.400
question from the chat. I don't normally have the ability to do this, but I saw one from the chat

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:12.400
from, let me see, from Runhua who always asks amazing questions. And it's in Slido as an

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:20.159
anonymous question, but I was wondering if you'd be able to unmute and ask that. Runhua, let me

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:31.039
see if I can find you. Oh, yeah. I think, you can hear me? Yes, yes. Yeah, for the large model,

00:10:31.039 --> 00:10:40.159
the general AI is expanding and game changer. And I just wondering how do you make sure your

00:10:40.719 --> 00:10:51.679
AI pipeline is accurate and ethical and under regulation because you are healthcare data,

00:10:51.679 --> 00:10:57.119
so that's more like restricted. Yeah. Yeah. I mean, you're spot on. And the departments of

00:10:57.119 --> 00:11:03.840
insurance, which regulate us in our states, are fairly skeptical of AI at the moment. Some states,

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:07.599
I would say, are outright hostile towards it. That's maybe a bit of an overstatement. But

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:12.719
definitely asking questions about AI and your AI governance and how you're thinking about that.

00:11:12.719 --> 00:11:17.599
The way we've chosen to do it is a little bit of a guilty until proven innocent approach,

00:11:17.599 --> 00:11:21.679
where you're effectively not allowed to use AI until you've gone through an approval process

00:11:21.679 --> 00:11:26.239
that says, yes, you can. I think as we learn more about it, we'll probably change that approach.

00:11:26.239 --> 00:11:33.520
But as of right now, it's a two stage process. The first approval is we have a use case for AI.

00:11:34.159 --> 00:11:37.119
We pull together the documentation, and it's pretty quick. It's not a big deal.

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:41.840
It goes to a team that thinks about it through an ethics bias governance lens.

00:11:42.559 --> 00:11:48.799
And they'll ask questions like, what data is being used? Is that data staying within a dedicated

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:54.159
tenant? Or is it being used to train a public model? So open versus closed LLM. Does the data

00:11:54.159 --> 00:12:01.119
ever leave shore? What tool are you going to use? And really what that team is trying,

00:12:01.119 --> 00:12:06.080
that approval process is really trying to answer two questions is, are we OK and proud of what's

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:12.239
happening with the data for this use case? And then should AI be used in this use case?

00:12:12.239 --> 00:12:15.679
And sometimes we're finding it's really, it's somebody wanting to do something fun and cool,

00:12:15.679 --> 00:12:21.919
and there's actually a better way to do it that's not AI anyway. So stage one is what tool and what

00:12:21.919 --> 00:12:26.719
is happening with the data? What's our data posture? Stage two, assuming it passes one,

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:31.200
is more where the CTO and the architects get involved. Are we going to have to integrate?

00:12:31.840 --> 00:12:35.039
Are we going to have to punch a hole in a firewall to get to an external tool?

00:12:35.039 --> 00:12:39.760
So it's a little bit more around the technical, how would we do it? And do we have the resources

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:44.400
to throw at this? And is it worth our time to do it? So it's a two stage process. The assumption

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:49.280
is you cannot use AI. And then further down the road, you can prove your case and get the approval

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:55.039
to use it. I love that, Toby. Thank you. I especially love the acknowledgement that

00:12:55.039 --> 00:12:59.840
sometimes the answer is just like, oh, we could do that with AI, but we could also just not use

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:04.960
AI and still do it just fine. Yeah. Oh, yeah. Well, and the funny thing, it's funny you say

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:11.200
that, Libby, because I also, I sit on this beast, the IAA, International Actuarial Association. I

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:15.919
sit on an AI task force for them. We just had a call last week. And in Europe, and if there's

00:13:15.919 --> 00:13:21.679
Europeans out here, please chime in in the chat. I'd love to hear your thoughts. AI is being

00:13:21.679 --> 00:13:27.840
thought of more from the environmental or carbon footprint of AI. And they're looking at it more,

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:32.400
every time you send that chat GPT or copilot query, you're basically ripping down a tree

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:36.719
somewhere. So be careful when you use it. And they're saying, yeah, we shouldn't always use AI.

00:13:36.719 --> 00:13:42.400
It's not always something that has to happen. So it has been interesting to hear that, that there is

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:47.440
this awareness that AI might work and might be a candidate solution, but it doesn't have to always

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:52.400
be the solution. Yeah. I'm finding often that people are like, oh, here's all these things

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:57.679
that AI can do. And that helps them think about use cases, which is sort of a backwards pipeline.

00:13:59.679 --> 00:14:05.679
But then if you talk to more people who are really experienced in things like NLP, you realize, oh,

00:14:05.679 --> 00:14:11.039
wait, we can just use NLP to do this and you don't have to use AI and we'll be just fine.

00:14:11.919 --> 00:14:15.039
Well, and I think, sorry to jump in there, but the other thing that I think different,

00:14:15.039 --> 00:14:18.559
yeah, the other thing that to me, at least differentiates AI from other things we've seen,

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:24.880
just because of the scale of what it is, is it seems like other things that in my working career

00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:28.640
have revolutionized things. I think like the adoption of the internet, that was something

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:33.280
that technology came along. Then we all figured out how to adopt it and implement it. And it

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:38.640
certainly did change things. No question about it. AI, the fundamental pieces of AI have been around

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:42.880
forever, since the fifties. We've just never had big enough data sets and enough compute power to

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:46.559
do it. So it's like, this is a weird case where the technology has caught up with the science.

00:14:46.559 --> 00:14:50.479
It used to be the other way around. And so I think we're all struggling with that just a little bit.

00:14:51.599 --> 00:14:59.039
Yeah. All right. Great. Fantastic question. Rudhwa, I'm going to look through Slido here

00:14:59.039 --> 00:15:02.479
because we suddenly have a bunch more Slido questions, which is amazing.

00:15:03.039 --> 00:15:03.539
Awesome.

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:12.400
I have an anonymous question here that is a little bit more of a career advice question,

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:18.320
if you're up for that. I will highlight it in Slido so everybody knows. My career background

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:24.640
is as a data scientist. I have just made the step up to management and I'm feeling a bit overwhelmed.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:30.719
What advice can you give me and how can I know if I'm doing a good job? And you had a pipeline of

00:15:31.440 --> 00:15:35.520
moving into bigger and scarier roles. Maybe you have a little bit to share here.

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:41.440
Yeah, it is a good question. I love this question too. And I'll go back and give a little bit of

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:47.359
background. Not that I want it to be biography or anything, but my bachelor's degree is in

00:15:47.359 --> 00:15:51.840
statistics and math. And when I got a bachelor's degree, I thought, okay, great, cool. What do you

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:57.599
do with a bachelor's degree in stats? And it turns out probably not a ton. If you get lucky and you

00:15:57.599 --> 00:16:01.359
find a niche, that's great. Master's degree or doctorate for sure, but a bachelor's degree,

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:05.919
a little bit limited. So I wasn't really sure what I was going to do. I stuck around, did some

00:16:05.919 --> 00:16:10.960
research with a professor, took some graduate courses, ended up thinking teaching could be

00:16:10.960 --> 00:16:15.359
the thing. So I ended up actually went back post-baccalaureate and I taught. I was a high

00:16:15.359 --> 00:16:19.919
school teacher for a while. I taught high school all day and I taught at a college at night. I

00:16:19.919 --> 00:16:24.159
thought everybody worked from 7 a.m. to 10 p.m. I thought that was normal. Turns out it's not.

00:16:24.719 --> 00:16:30.960
And along the way, I kind of stumbled onto the actuarial career and resigned from the teaching

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:35.599
role and went into the actuarial role full tilt and did a little stint in consulting, ended up

00:16:35.599 --> 00:16:41.119
here at Delta and worked my way up. And throughout there, there were always those challenges. And this

00:16:41.119 --> 00:16:44.719
comes back full circle to the question. There were always those opportunities. There were always

00:16:44.719 --> 00:16:50.320
those challenges. Even if it was within the actuarial lane, like taking on a new sub team,

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:56.239
or maybe taking accountability for underwriting as well as actuarial. And for me, those leadership

00:16:56.239 --> 00:17:00.799
roles, I just always, I never said no. I always knew and I trusted that I could figure it out.

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:05.920
If you think you shouldn't say yes to it until you have it figured out, you'll never say yes

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:10.160
to it because newsflash, nobody ever has it figured out. The first time you lead teams,

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:14.800
you're going to realize that it's never quite what you think it is. In fact, I have to check

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:19.520
myself when people come into my office and say, hey, you know, I want to get into management.

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:23.359
I have to make sure I take an inquisitive tone. I have to say, oh, really? Why? When in reality,

00:17:23.359 --> 00:17:29.359
I want to say, why? Like, why would you want to do that? But it is also very incredibly rewarding

00:17:29.359 --> 00:17:36.079
along the way. I would argue that the biggest thing you can do if you want to succeed in a

00:17:36.079 --> 00:17:42.000
leadership role is no matter what advice you get, there's an underlying assumption of all of it

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.079
that you know your team. You can't actually implement any of that advice if you don't

00:17:46.079 --> 00:17:50.319
actually get to know your team, and you'd be shocked how many managers skip that step,

00:17:50.319 --> 00:17:53.359
especially if they inherit a new team that's not theirs. They just kind of skip over it.

00:17:54.560 --> 00:17:57.680
I tell my folks, and I tell you, I'm pointing to the other building because that's where they're

00:17:57.680 --> 00:18:00.800
sitting. They're all, and probably Shikha is going to plug her ears here in a minute because

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:05.839
she knows I'm going to say it. Managing, I think it's a four-step process, and we overthink it very,

00:18:05.839 --> 00:18:10.719
very frequently, but it is the same four steps just on rinse and repeat. That's not to say

00:18:10.719 --> 00:18:14.400
they're easy, but it is the same four. So, I mean, if you take anything from it, I would take this.

00:18:14.719 --> 00:18:19.760
Step number one is put the right people in the right role, and that's an ongoing battle.

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:23.760
The minute you get your chessboard set up, the game changes or the opponent moves or whatever.

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:27.839
You got to move people around. I just this morning moved some people around, and some were happy,

00:18:27.839 --> 00:18:31.599
some were not, but it had to be done. So, putting the right people in the right role,

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:35.520
and then as a leader, you have to give them the right vision of what you're trying to accomplish.

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:38.719
Make sure it's really clear, and we're all aligned on what that is and why we're doing it.

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:44.079
Give them the right culture to get it done, and then the biggest one, number four, is get out of

00:18:44.079 --> 00:18:49.520
their way, and if you've done the first three, you got the right people, you gave them the right

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:53.199
vision, you gave them the right culture, you should be delighted to get out of their way and

00:18:53.199 --> 00:18:57.839
let them do their thing. They will knock it out of the park every time. If you're not willing to

00:18:57.839 --> 00:19:01.920
just get out of the way, you probably need to look in the mirror because you either didn't do steps

00:19:01.920 --> 00:19:06.479
one through three correctly, could be true, or your ego won't let you get out of the way, and

00:19:06.479 --> 00:19:11.280
you're in there micromanaging when you shouldn't be. So, it's the same four steps. Right people in

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:17.280
the right role, vision, culture, stay out of the way, and you'll be shocked. I'm so impressed by

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:27.839
Rachel who just put your four steps in the chat. Oh, wow. That was so nice. All right. Thank you,

00:19:27.839 --> 00:19:34.800
Rachel. There's a fantastic question, and also, like, anonymous asker, what a good question.

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:38.319
Thank you so much. I wish you would put your name on this so I could thank you. If this was you,

00:19:38.959 --> 00:19:47.680
send me or Rachel, like, a DM in the chat. There is a question from Sarah, which is really

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:51.280
right in line with this. It's a great follow-up. She says that she cannot unmute, so I'm going to

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:56.640
ask it for her, and I will also stick it in the chat so everybody can see. It's how do you match

00:19:56.640 --> 00:20:01.599
the team's skills and interests to projects that are coming down the line? So, is leadership

00:20:01.599 --> 00:20:07.520
receptive to new data science techniques or products, or do they take some persuading? I think

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:12.959
that's kind of two different questions. Yeah, I think it is, too. Yeah, it is two different

00:20:12.959 --> 00:20:17.040
questions, and I'll answer them both. So, the first one, how do you put the right people in

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:20.400
the right role? I think, again, it comes back, you've got to know your team. You've got to know

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:24.800
their interests. You've got to know their skills, strengths, weaknesses, and I'm a firm believer in

00:20:24.800 --> 00:20:30.640
the stretch assignment that you think they can accomplish and pull off. However, you've got to

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:34.400
make sure you're not stretching them so much that it's demoralizing, and that really just means you

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:38.160
really do have to get to know them and get in there and understand what makes them tick a little

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:45.119
bit, and the support along the way is important. Just one little anecdote. We were kicking off a

00:20:45.119 --> 00:20:51.040
major project a couple years ago, and our normal cadre of leaders were all way overcommitted,

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:57.439
and so we picked somebody who I thought was a year or two or maybe three away from taking that

00:20:57.439 --> 00:21:02.640
sort of a leadership role, but we had no choice. We had to let her jump in early, and we did. We

00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:06.000
brought her in a room, and she said, you know, hey, I could do this one of two ways. She laid

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.920
out two approaches, and she said, what do you think, and the minute I looked at her, and I said,

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:13.439
no, no, Maddie, it's not what I think. What do you think? What do you think we ought to be doing

00:21:13.439 --> 00:21:19.439
here? She immediately was 12 feet tall, and she walked out of the room. She's like, I get it. I

00:21:19.439 --> 00:21:23.920
get what I own this. It's me. I got to run with this. I said, exactly. She ran. She left the room,

00:21:23.920 --> 00:21:26.880
and I immediately looked at her boss, though, and I said, do not let her screw this up, or we're

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:31.280
going to ruin her forever, so we've got to support her and make sure she succeeds. The one time she

00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:35.680
sticks her neck out and says, I'm going to own this, and I'm going to run with it, maybe a year

00:21:35.680 --> 00:21:41.520
or two early. If she fails, then we've ruined her, and we did not. We made sure she was successful.

00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:45.119
Oh, good. I was going to say, we kind of did an update.

00:21:45.119 --> 00:21:51.040
No, no, no. It was awful, so I think the first question is those challenge assignments that put

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:57.040
people on a path to a career. I'm a firm believer employees need to own their own career development.

00:21:57.599 --> 00:22:03.119
You, as their manager, you support them. You get roadblocks out of their way, but they have to own

00:22:03.119 --> 00:22:07.760
their own career. This is not for you to do for them, and I think that's true the further up they

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:12.959
go. If they're entry-level, you got to own a little bit of it, but the further up, when

00:22:12.959 --> 00:22:16.479
somebody's been promoted once, twice, three times, you should be owning less and less of the career

00:22:16.479 --> 00:22:21.839
the whole way along. The second question, though, was management being ready for new techniques.

00:22:21.839 --> 00:22:26.640
You do have to do a little bit of a marketing thing. Being able to communicate the results and

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:31.199
explain them is a huge, I would argue that's the lion's share of does it actually succeed

00:22:31.199 --> 00:22:36.560
and go to a production-ready or not. I used to say it with actuaries. I'll say it with data

00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:42.479
scientists. Now, I will take a mediocre data scientist with excellent communication skills

00:22:43.199 --> 00:22:47.040
over an excellent data scientist with mediocre communication skills any day of the week.

00:22:48.719 --> 00:22:52.959
It really is an internal marketing thing, especially when we're lobbying for dollars

00:22:52.959 --> 00:22:57.199
and resources. Sometimes you're talking with departments. That's not the world they live in.

00:22:57.199 --> 00:23:02.000
They're not in the data all day. They're not up to date on the latest models or vocabulary,

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.880
so you do have to do a little bit of a marketing campaign with it.

00:23:06.959 --> 00:23:13.280
Amazing. Toby, I feel like this has turned into the career advice session that I did not know

00:23:13.280 --> 00:23:20.000
that I needed. Rachel put a question in the chat that I would love it if everybody could go

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:26.000
hop in and talk about, which is what are some tips for leaning into those challenge assignments

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:34.719
as the individual contributor? She also asked, how do you identify the challenge assignments?

00:23:34.719 --> 00:23:38.719
That could be on both sides. How do you know this is the right thing with the stakes that

00:23:38.719 --> 00:23:43.520
are right to give to somebody? Then how, as an individual contributor, do you say,

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:48.800
that's going to be worth stressing myself out for? That's going to be worth the challenge

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:55.280
because I really want to do this. What we've been successful doing, both in our

00:23:55.280 --> 00:24:00.800
data science area and in the broader tech area, is taking huge initiatives that we all well

00:24:00.800 --> 00:24:05.599
understand. They're just mammoth kind of things. Rewriting an entire application from scratch,

00:24:05.599 --> 00:24:09.199
which isn't all going to be a two, three-year project, but being able to break it apart into

00:24:09.199 --> 00:24:14.640
pieces and smaller bite-sized pieces that you can let somebody stand up and own this small piece.

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:18.239
It might only be 10% of the whole project, but it's a critical part and they know it. They

00:24:18.239 --> 00:24:22.880
understand its part and let them own a small part of it. Now, not every project lends itself

00:24:22.880 --> 00:24:27.119
to being broken down that way, but don't be shy about spending a day or two with a whiteboard

00:24:27.119 --> 00:24:31.920
trying to figure out ways to do it because it'll pay off. That's on the giving of the assignment.

00:24:32.719 --> 00:24:38.319
On the receiving of the assignment side, I don't know that I've ever said no to a stretch

00:24:38.319 --> 00:24:42.880
assignment that was thrown my way. I think you can find the lesson to be learned in pretty much

00:24:42.880 --> 00:24:48.800
all of them, but don't let yourself get in over your head. If you can find a mentor,

00:24:48.800 --> 00:24:54.079
if you can find somebody in an adjacent area, or if you are doing that 10% of a big project,

00:24:54.079 --> 00:24:58.959
some of the other people that are owning the other pieces and make sure you're asking for help,

00:24:58.959 --> 00:25:05.359
you're bouncing ideas off early. I have no problem with a new leader getting in over their head and

00:25:05.359 --> 00:25:10.640
we have a $10,000 mistake. I'm good with that. I just don't want a $10 million mistake. Call for

00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:15.439
the help early if you need it. Awesome. That was my question about stakes was like,

00:25:15.439 --> 00:25:20.239
what is the right stake level for giving someone something that they need the leeway to make a

00:25:20.239 --> 00:25:26.000
mistake on? Because that's one of those things. If you're giving a big project that you cannot make

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:30.640
a mistake on, failure is not an option. To me, I'm going to say no to that one because I always

00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:36.959
need that leeway when I'm doing something big and new. All right. That was a wonderful question,

00:25:36.959 --> 00:25:43.439
Sarah, and wonderful follow-up, Rachel. Thank you so much, both of you. We had a question in

00:25:43.439 --> 00:25:48.160
the Slido, which I think we can cover really quickly. It's a bit of an oddball question,

00:25:48.160 --> 00:25:52.880
but it's never been asked before, so this is interesting. It's, do you share your data as

00:25:52.880 --> 00:26:02.000
an API or for research? Now, your data is probably full of PII, right? You cannot do that, but do you

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:08.160
know of anybody who does? Because businesses and organizations consume third-party data,

00:26:08.160 --> 00:26:14.239
but we don't ever really talk about whether or not they put data back out there. Yeah, so oddly,

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:20.640
anonymized and de-identified data, HIPAA has some fairly strict standards of what qualifies as

00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:24.160
de-identified. The good news with that is there's tools that'll de-identify it for you.

00:26:25.280 --> 00:26:31.040
So we do use a few of those tools, and we have. We've collaborated with research organizations.

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:36.959
We've collaborated with some private third parties. We tend to, this is a weird distinction,

00:26:36.959 --> 00:26:41.280
but if we do that, we make sure we've got all the right governance in place and the

00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:46.000
right permissions. We tend to do it for free because we don't ever want to be in a position

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:50.640
where we've profited by selling the data. Like, that's just a bad look. If we're doing it and

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:54.640
there's an oral health research project that's likely going to contribute to the body of

00:26:54.640 --> 00:26:58.959
knowledge around oral health, that's a worthwhile thing to do. We don't want to be seen as profiting

00:26:58.959 --> 00:27:04.160
from it, though, for all the right reasons. The other thing I would say we have to be mindful of

00:27:05.040 --> 00:27:09.199
is we have some large dental customers that just forbid us from doing it under any circumstances.

00:27:09.199 --> 00:27:14.880
So we have to pull their data out, which is fine, well understood. The other piece is a fair number

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:21.359
of our customers, and probably a lot of the people on this call, are covered by a dental plan where

00:27:21.359 --> 00:27:25.599
your employer actually still retains all the risk. It's not actually an insurance company that

00:27:25.599 --> 00:27:31.359
retains the risk. The insurance company processes the claim, maintains the network, but in effect

00:27:31.359 --> 00:27:35.199
pays it out of your employer's checking account. It's not really how it goes, but effectively.

00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:40.560
And in those cases, it's not really even our data. We're merely custodians and we possess the

00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:44.479
data, but we don't own the data. And so in those cases, we need those customers to give us

00:27:44.479 --> 00:27:49.760
affirmative approval to use it in that way. That makes sense. What a great question. That was an

00:27:49.760 --> 00:27:56.800
anonymous one. Yeah. Kudos to you because it's one that has literally never come across.

00:27:57.439 --> 00:28:02.400
Yeah. And one thing on that data topic, one thing that makes it interesting for us is we

00:28:02.400 --> 00:28:07.839
have some customers, one of my favorite customers I work with, we have been their dental insurance

00:28:07.839 --> 00:28:14.800
plan since 1974. And they have long tenured employees, some multi-generational employees.

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:18.959
So there are thousands actually. It's not just like one or two, thousands of people out there

00:28:18.959 --> 00:28:24.719
that are in their sixties now or fifties that have never had any coverage other than Delta

00:28:24.719 --> 00:28:29.359
Dental through us for their entire lives. So if you want to ask what happens in a person's mouth

00:28:29.359 --> 00:28:34.959
from birth to age 60, we actually have a sample of thousands where we can actually credibly talk

00:28:34.959 --> 00:28:40.560
about that, this idea of continuously eligible members. And that makes the data pretty fun to

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:47.520
play. Amazing. Toby, Isabella had requested Delta Dental's tooth fairy data.

00:28:50.319 --> 00:28:55.199
We do a study every year and the tooth fairy has gotten outrageously expensive lately.

00:28:56.319 --> 00:29:00.079
The Delta Dental Plant Association does actually publish a survey every year of what is the going

00:29:00.079 --> 00:29:08.560
rate for the tooth fairy. And it's more than you think. Hilarious. All right. Let's move on to a

00:29:08.560 --> 00:29:14.479
question in Slido from Zach. And Zach has a little asterisk next to his question, which means

00:29:14.479 --> 00:29:20.239
I will ask it for him. If anybody ever wants to ask a question, but you can't ask it,

00:29:20.239 --> 00:29:23.280
you always put an asterisk in there, a little note that says, Libby, can you read this?

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.959
Zach says, when you're looking to add new team members to your team, what are some green flags

00:29:28.959 --> 00:29:37.040
that stand out beyond the qualification and the job description? Questions are moving around. I'm

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:41.680
going to highlight Zach so it doesn't move around for me. So has that changed in recent years?

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:46.959
Because the number of applicants has increased and the number of new roles has decreased. And

00:29:46.959 --> 00:29:50.400
if anybody else has been through the job search in the past couple of years, you know that you

00:29:50.400 --> 00:29:55.599
go look at a job on LinkedIn and it's been posted for two hours and it's got 500 applicants on it,

00:29:55.599 --> 00:30:02.079
right? And you're like, oh no. So this is a great question, Zach. It is. It's outstanding. So I

00:30:02.079 --> 00:30:05.839
would say when we're screening and triaging resumes, particularly in the data science area,

00:30:06.719 --> 00:30:10.640
what I push the team, and Shikha's on the line, she can certainly jump into if she needs to,

00:30:11.599 --> 00:30:17.199
we look for balance in that team. As I mentioned earlier, data science is such a broad range of

00:30:17.839 --> 00:30:22.640
skill sets and a broad range of domains that are relevant. We've all seen the VED diagram of what

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:26.719
makes a good data scientist. That's kind of verbally where I'm going. And you're not going

00:30:26.719 --> 00:30:31.280
to find very many of those unicorns that live right in that sweet spot of overlap. So you're

00:30:31.359 --> 00:30:37.199
going to have team members that are maybe a little bit stronger on like the ML ops side of things.

00:30:37.199 --> 00:30:40.239
You're going to have a team member who's maybe a little bit better with the data engineering,

00:30:40.239 --> 00:30:43.920
somebody who's a little more domain knowledge, somebody that's a little more modeling and

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:48.000
statistics oriented. And it's about balancing the team. So when there's an opening, it's like,

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:51.439
okay, what are we missing? What do we need a little bit more horsepower? Let's triage the

00:30:51.439 --> 00:30:56.959
resumes and go try to find that gap if there is one. So that would be sort of one. The other

00:30:56.959 --> 00:31:03.920
piece I would say is kind of what you were just hinting at. The job market is flipped on us where

00:31:03.920 --> 00:31:07.680
an opening goes out and we're getting hundreds of resumes. I mean, even for a summer internship,

00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:13.920
we got like triple digits in terms of resumes. And that's a lot to go through. And what I think

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:20.880
makes it particularly challenging is there's no barrier to calling yourself a data scientist.

00:31:21.839 --> 00:31:26.560
I joke, but I don't think I'm far off where you can have a resume for a position that

00:31:26.880 --> 00:31:31.920
the person, the candidate, maybe she has a PhD in math and she's done a ton of this work for years

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:35.920
and she's super well experienced and she calls herself a data scientist. The next applicant

00:31:36.719 --> 00:31:41.439
has a sociology degree, which that's a perfectly fine degree, but took one stats course along the

00:31:41.439 --> 00:31:44.479
way and they're calling themselves a data scientist. And when you dig in, it's like,

00:31:44.479 --> 00:31:49.280
well, I can open Excel and I can do save and save as. So I'm a data scientist. And that's not

00:31:49.280 --> 00:31:55.280
exactly what we're after. So vetting through that can be a tough, tough thing. What I've

00:31:55.280 --> 00:32:02.160
decided lately because of that is the right way to go here is we're big on interviewing for

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:09.920
traits, not skills. Skills, as long as you're somewhat technically inclined, you can pick up

00:32:09.920 --> 00:32:13.839
the skills along the way. I mean, that's one of the beautiful things about Python and to maybe a

00:32:13.839 --> 00:32:18.800
lesser degree ours, it is pretty easy to pick up if you're technically inclined. And things like

00:32:18.800 --> 00:32:25.359
RStudio make it easy to do. So I would say we're less cranked up about discrete skills,

00:32:25.359 --> 00:32:30.400
more traits. And by traits, I mean, are you curious? Do you ask good questions? Are you

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:36.239
a lifelong learner? How are you going to work in a team? How do you attack a big problem? Do you

00:32:36.239 --> 00:32:41.760
try to solve it all at one time and you have that no progress, no progress, then at once it all kind

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:46.319
of snaps together. Is that your mode of solving it? And that's fine. Or are you a break it apart

00:32:46.319 --> 00:32:50.239
into small pieces and solve it? And we need both. We just need to make sure we're getting the right

00:32:50.239 --> 00:32:55.359
balance. So we spend a lot of time in the interview and screening process trying to get to those

00:32:55.359 --> 00:33:01.040
traits rather than discrete skills. My other reason, and this applies more on the application

00:33:01.040 --> 00:33:07.119
development arm of my job, perhaps, is we found when we were really cranked up about skills,

00:33:07.119 --> 00:33:12.959
like do you have the latest Java certifications, those types of things, by the time a skill is

00:33:13.920 --> 00:33:18.880
realized in the marketplace, it's adopted by a university curriculum, they pump out a couple

00:33:18.880 --> 00:33:24.239
of graduating classes, there's some certifications achieved, that's probably five or six years on a

00:33:24.239 --> 00:33:30.560
date already. So getting all cranked up about a particular certification or skill, I'm probably

00:33:30.560 --> 00:33:38.239
less excited about. Yeah, there's a little conversation in the chat about all of the

00:33:38.319 --> 00:33:46.719
different things that the same job title can be. And even the job description sometimes,

00:33:46.719 --> 00:33:50.800
you get into the job interview and you're like, oh, what you want isn't even what's in the job

00:33:50.800 --> 00:33:55.359
description. Yeah. And I love this one. I've interviewed STEM PhDs who call themselves data

00:33:55.359 --> 00:33:59.599
scientists and can't answer that. That's the other problem is, yeah, they may know the domain,

00:33:59.599 --> 00:34:05.119
but you ask them how to join two tables or what's wrong with this join. You assume they are kind of

00:34:05.119 --> 00:34:09.919
deer in the headlights. So it's, yeah, that is a great point too. You can go too far the wrong way.

00:34:10.800 --> 00:34:16.239
I think that this is a good time to say what I always say, which is data science is not one

00:34:16.239 --> 00:34:21.919
thing. If you are not the flavor of data science that Toby needs for his team, you probably are

00:34:21.919 --> 00:34:25.760
the flavor of data science that somebody else needs for their team, because they do need that

00:34:25.760 --> 00:34:30.639
deep subject matter expertise. And it matters a little bit less that you know how to do specific

00:34:31.360 --> 00:34:35.439
technical things. So there is a place for everybody out there. I think it's a,

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:40.399
it's a really, really tough thing writing a job description. And it's also a really,

00:34:40.399 --> 00:34:43.840
really tough thing being a job applicant and reading through a job description.

00:34:44.639 --> 00:34:49.919
So it's tough on both sides. And yet, Shikha, if you ever wanted to hop in, Rachel said in the chat,

00:34:50.479 --> 00:34:57.600
let us know if you have something to say in kind of support or augmenting any of Toby's answers

00:34:57.600 --> 00:35:02.479
here. Zach, fantastic question. We have some more stuff.

00:35:02.479 --> 00:35:04.879
Sorry, I was figuring out how to unmute Shikha real quick.

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:05.919
Oh, yeah.

00:35:05.919 --> 00:35:06.399
